<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="48" type="diagnostic characters">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">Diagnostic characters</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">
.Very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
, from which it can be separated only on details of the male terminalia. Zaitzev &amp; Polevoi (2002) used four key characters to distinguish them: 1) Apical process of the gonostylus slightly bolder and with more developed unsclerotized area around base of this process; 2) Dentations on the inner surface of gonostylus being restricted to distal part, not reaching the curve basally; 3) Apical part of tergite IX less sclerotized; 4) Details of aedeagus as figured by them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">The species is known only from the holotype from Tadzhikistan.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="48" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="48">
The species limit between 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia hissarica" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hissarica">Katatopygia hissarica</taxonomicName>
seems vague, and it is possibly that 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia hissarica" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hissarica">Katatopygia hissarica</taxonomicName>
will fall inside the variation of 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen, 2012" authorityName="Martinsson &amp; Kjaerandsen" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Katatopygia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Katatopygia erythropyga" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropyga">Katatopygia erythropyga</taxonomicName>
when a wider range of material is studied.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
